userreviews.userReview:
This is a revised review as of 4/14/2013. Several of the images were off Google Image detailing the graphic novel for visual impact but this is an actual review of the novel. Tale focuses on a man, well, not just a man, but, a wizard in current day Chicago who uses his magical powers to solve mysteries. Most of them focus on the supernatural and there's a whole underbelly of mythical creatures which mortals are mostly unaware of . .. vampires, werewolves, enemy wizards, faeries, ghosts, etc. 
STRENGTHS (1) Innovative ideas which hasn't been pursued effectively in quite some time; (2) Typical wise cracking P.I. type with some funny lines; (3) Follows a lot of plot/story elements of the typical investigation;
(4) Oh so kewl explanation of how magic works which are typically overly detailed in most fantasy tales (Thirdeye, Soulgaze and Doom of Damocles among others); (5) Great climatic ending (writing this revised review makes me want to reread it); (6) A funny talking skull named Bob; (7) Teaches you how to defeat a demon that's banging on your door; and (8) Shows you how to be one of the good guys. NOT SO GOOD (1) A few cliches at time but nothing to make you want to throw the book against the wall, like other fantasy tales, and yeah, I'm looking at you Terry Goodkind; (2) subplot love story felt sophomoric (though it had some funny moments when it wasn't trying to be serious); and(3) Wizard's rants about how he wishes to treat women sometimes feels, well, not so believable. Dude, wake up.That said, it's still easily in the top three for the year (if you appreciate light fantasy) and refreshingly different, so, HOORAY!!!! CHARACTERS/DIALOGUE: B; STORY/PLOTTING/EDITING: B; WRITING STYLE: B to B plus; WORLD BUILDING: B plus; WHEN READ: 2007 (second reading) (revised review 4/14/2013); OVERALL GRADE: B to B plus.
